t their lives and view the world around them. With rare immediacy, The Silk Weavers of Kyoto captures a way of life that is rapidly disappearing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aSilk industryxJapanxKyoto. 0aSilk industryzJapanzKyoto. 0aSilk weavingxJapanxKyoto. 0aSilk weavingzJapanzKyoto. 0aWeaversxJapanxKyoto. 0aWeaverszJapanzKyoto. 0aWork and familyxJapanxKyoto. 0aWork and familyzJapanzKyoto. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aacademic.  acareer.  acraftsmen.  adying art.  aeconomic.  aeconomics.  aendangered species.  afabric workers.  afamily life.  agenerational.  ahistorical.  ainterviews.  ajapanese culture.  ajapanese fashion.  akimono.  akyoto.  alife history.  alife story.  amanufacturers.  amarket.  arelationships.  ascholarly.  asupply and demand.  atextile workers.  atrue story.  aweavers.  aweaving.  awork.  aworkplace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093576140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520935761423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520935761/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles